{"title_page": "Without a Song", "text_new": "\"'''Without a Song'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]] with music by [[Vincent Youmans]] and lyrics by [[Billy Rose]] and [[Edward Eliscu]], published in 1929. It was included in the [[musical play]], ''Great Day''.  The play only ran for 36 performances but contained two songs which became famous, \"Without a Song\" and \"Great Day\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet Broadway Database|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/great-day-10960|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=April 29, 2017}}</ref> \n\n==Background and initial recordings==\nCanadian singer, Gilbert Burgess Holland introduced \u201cWithout A Song\u201d in the show \u201cGreat Day\u201d accompanied by Fletcher Henderson\u2019s Orchestra, in the pit of the famous Park Theatre, NYC. <ref>{{https://archive.org/stream/RecordResearch37/RR%2037_djvu.txt}}</ref> Gilbert is the son of Reverend [[John Christie Holland]].  One of the earliest recordings of the song was by [[Paul Whiteman]]'s orchestra featuring [[Bing Crosby]] on October 9, 1929<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/crosby1a.html|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=April 29, 2017}}</ref> and this reached the charts of the day.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/452 452]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/452}}</ref><br />\n\"Without a Song\" was recorded in March 1946 in New York by [[Billy Eckstine]],<ref>Billy Eckstine, I Ain't Like That, Quadromania, Jazz Edition, 4CD, Mebran International GmbH, 2005</ref> who later rerecorded the song live on 30 August 1960 at the Cloud Nine Lounge of the New Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas for his album [[No Cover, No Minimum]]. <br />\n\"Without a Song\" also was recorded twice by [[Perry Como]]: the first time on January 11, 1951 and the second time in June 1970 at a live performance at the International Hotel, Las Vegas, Nevada. The 1951 recording was issued as a 78 rpm single in the United States by [[RCA Victor Records]] (catalog number 20-4033) and in the United Kingdom by [[HMV]] (catalog number B-10093). It was also included in a 1957 album, ''Dream Along With Me'' (RCA Camden catalog number CAL-403). The 1970 recording was issued on albums by RCA and its United Kingdom, Netherlands, and Japan subsidiaries, but not as a single.<ref>{{cite web|title=Perry Como Discography|url=http://kokomo.ca/early_years/without_a_song.htm|website=kokomo.ca|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable recordings==\n[[Lawrence Tibbett]], [[Nelson Eddy]] and [[Frank Sinatra]] recorded versions of the song with what appears to be the original lyrics, including the line, \"A [[List of ethnic slurs#D|darkie]]'s born, but he's no good no how, without a song.\" In subsequent recordings, Sinatra didn't use the term \"darkie\", and later recorded versions included the altered text \"a man is born, but he's no good no how, without a song.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blacksuperhero.com/articles/art2-Cohen.html|title= A Face On the Past|author= Richard Cohen}}{{dead link}}</ref> The original was played in error on BBC Radio 4's 'PM' program on the 9th April 2020, prompting an apology on the same program four days later.\n\nIn addition to popular artists like Bing Crosby, Perry Como, Frank Sinatra, [[Tony Bennett]], [[Keely Smith]] and [[Neil Sedaka]], and opera singers like [[Lauritz Melchior]], [[Jan Peerce]] and [[Mario Lanza]], many African-American artists of varying styles also successfully recorded the song after Billy Eckstine first did so in 1946, including a version in \"gospel style\" by [[Mahalia Jackson]] in concert in Berlin, 1967; also versions by [[George Benson]], [[The Ravens]], [[The Isley Brothers]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[The Supremes]] (for their album ''[[I Hear a Symphony (album)|I Hear A Symphony]]''), and jazz singer [[Jimmy Scott]] on his 2006 album ''Milestone Profiles - Jimmy Scott'' on Milestone Records. Instrumental versions have been recorded by [[Sonny Rollins]], on his 1962 \"comeback\" album, ''[[The Bridge (Sonny Rollins album)|The Bridge]]'', [[Stanley Turrentine]] on his album ''Never Let Me Go'' (Blue Note 90838), [[Clare Fischer]] on ''[[Surging Ahead]]'' (Pacific Jazz PJ 67), and [[Bill Evans]] on ''[[You Must Believe in Spring (Bill Evans album)|You Must Believe in Spring]]'' (reissued on [[Rhino Records]]). Others include [[Oscar Peterson]], [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Art Blakey]], [[Art Tatum]], [[Joe Henderson]], [[Freddie Hubbard]], [[Art Pepper]], [[Nana Mouskouri]] and [[Adam Rogers (musician)|Adam Rogers]].\n\n[[Al Jolson]] sang \"Without A Song\" on request from [[Oscar Levant]], and as the show's closing number, on the [[CBS]] [[Kraft Music Hall]] radio program, on the 21st of October 1948, accompanied by [[Lou Bring]] & His Orchestra & Chorus.\n\n\"Without a Song\" was released as a single in the UK by [[Gary Shearston]] in 1974 and by [[Noah Stewart]] in 2011.\n\n[[Willie Nelson]] used it as the [[Song|title track]] of a 1983 album.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Willie Nelson singles}}\n\n[[Category:Songs with music by Vincent Youmans]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Billy Rose]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Edward Eliscu]]\n[[Category:1929 songs]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters songs]]\n[[Category:Willie Nelson songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:The Supremes songs]]\n[[Category:1920s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Songs from musicals]]\n\n{{1920s-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\"'''Without a Song'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]] with music by [[Vincent Youmans]] and lyrics by [[Billy Rose]] and [[Edward Eliscu]], published in 1929. It was included in the [[musical play]], ''Great Day''.  The play only ran for 36 performances but contained two songs which became famous, \"Without a Song\" and \"Great Day\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet Broadway Database|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/great-day-10960|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=April 29, 2017}}</ref> \n\n==Background and initial recordings==\nCanadian singer, Gilbert Burgess Holland introduced \u201cWithout A Song\u201d in the show \u201cGreat Day\u201d accompanied by Fletcher Henderson\u2019s Orchestra, in the pit of the famous Park Theatre, NYC. <ref>{{https://archive.org/stream/RecordResearch37/RR%2037_djvu.txt}}</ref> Gilbert is the son of Reverend [[John Christie Holland]].  One of the earliest recordings of the song was by [[Paul Whiteman]]'s orchestra featuring [[Bing Crosby]] on October 9, 1929<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/crosby1a.html|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=April 29, 2017}}</ref> and this reached the charts of the day.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/452 452]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/452}}</ref><br />\n\"Without a Song\" was recorded in March 1946 in New York by [[Billy Eckstine]],<ref>Billy Eckstine, I Ain't Like That, Quadromania, Jazz Edition, 4CD, Mebran International GmbH, 2005</ref> who later rerecorded the song live on 30 August 1960 at the Cloud Nine Lounge of the New Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas for his album [[No Cover, No Minimum]]. <br />\n\"Without a Song\" also was recorded twice by [[Perry Como]]: the first time on January 11, 1951 and the second time in June 1970 at a live performance at the International Hotel, Las Vegas, Nevada. The 1951 recording was issued as a 78 rpm single in the United States by [[RCA Victor Records]] (catalog number 20-4033) and in the United Kingdom by [[HMV]] (catalog number B-10093). It was also included in a 1957 album, ''Dream Along With Me'' (RCA Camden catalog number CAL-403). The 1970 recording was issued on albums by RCA and its United Kingdom, Netherlands, and Japan subsidiaries, but not as a single.<ref>{{cite web|title=Perry Como Discography|url=http://kokomo.ca/early_years/without_a_song.htm|website=kokomo.ca|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable recordings==\n[[Lawrence Tibbett]], [[Nelson Eddy]] and [[Frank Sinatra]] recorded versions of the song with what appears to be the original lyrics, including the line, \"A [[List of ethnic slurs#D|darkie]]'s born, but he's no good no how, without a song.\" In subsequent recordings, Sinatra didn't use the term \"darkie\", and later recorded versions included the altered text \"a man is born, but he's no good no how, without a song.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/2000/10/26/a-face-on-the-past/e413f3a2-09d6-4ac4-9da4-a003a70481e7/|title= A Face On the Past|author= Richard Cohen}}{{dead link}}</ref> The original was played in error on BBC Radio 4's 'PM' program on the 9th April 2020, prompting an apology on the same program four days later.\n\nIn addition to popular artists like Bing Crosby, Perry Como, Frank Sinatra, [[Tony Bennett]], [[Keely Smith]] and [[Neil Sedaka]], and opera singers like [[Lauritz Melchior]], [[Jan Peerce]] and [[Mario Lanza]], many African-American artists of varying styles also successfully recorded the song after Billy Eckstine first did so in 1946, including a version in \"gospel style\" by [[Mahalia Jackson]] in concert in Berlin, 1967; also versions by [[George Benson]], [[The Ravens]], [[The Isley Brothers]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[The Supremes]] (for their album ''[[I Hear a Symphony (album)|I Hear A Symphony]]''), and jazz singer [[Jimmy Scott]] on his 2006 album ''Milestone Profiles - Jimmy Scott'' on Milestone Records. Instrumental versions have been recorded by [[Sonny Rollins]], on his 1962 \"comeback\" album, ''[[The Bridge (Sonny Rollins album)|The Bridge]]'', [[Stanley Turrentine]] on his album ''Never Let Me Go'' (Blue Note 90838), [[Clare Fischer]] on ''[[Surging Ahead]]'' (Pacific Jazz PJ 67), and [[Bill Evans]] on ''[[You Must Believe in Spring (Bill Evans album)|You Must Believe in Spring]]'' (reissued on [[Rhino Records]]). Others include [[Oscar Peterson]], [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Art Blakey]], [[Art Tatum]], [[Joe Henderson]], [[Freddie Hubbard]], [[Art Pepper]], [[Nana Mouskouri]] and [[Adam Rogers (musician)|Adam Rogers]].\n\n[[Al Jolson]] sang \"Without A Song\" on request from [[Oscar Levant]], and as the show's closing number, on the [[CBS]] [[Kraft Music Hall]] radio program, on the 21st of October 1948, accompanied by [[Lou Bring]] & His Orchestra & Chorus.\n\n\"Without a Song\" was released as a single in the UK by [[Gary Shearston]] in 1974 and by [[Noah Stewart]] in 2011.\n\n[[Willie Nelson]] used it as the [[Song|title track]] of a 1983 album.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Willie Nelson singles}}\n\n[[Category:Songs with music by Vincent Youmans]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Billy Rose]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Edward Eliscu]]\n[[Category:1929 songs]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters songs]]\n[[Category:Willie Nelson songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:The Supremes songs]]\n[[Category:1920s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Songs from musicals]]\n\n{{1920s-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "HYanWong", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Place dead link in correct location)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Without_a_Song"}
